(2, 81, 'Steve', 'steve@stevemessam.co.uk', 'http://www.stevemessam.wordpress.com', '90.202.125.137', '2010-09-29 10:51:12', '2010-09-29 10:51:12', 'If it splits easily it''s more likely to be shale or slate than sandstone - but happy to be proved wrong! Sandstone is generally crumbly and yellow (or red in Devon and Eden Valley - it''s an up and downy seam up the country). There is a very good geological online map (a bit like Google Earth for rocks). Worth tracking down.\r\nWell done for joining the blog world!', 0, '1', 'Mozilla/5.0 (Macintosh; U; PPC Mac OS X 10.4; en-US; rv:1.9.2.10) Gecko/20100914 Firefox/3.6.10', '', 0, 0),
(3, 9, 'Margaret', 'margaret@isherwood.org.uk', '', '86.154.163.165', '2010-09-29 11:26:43', '2010-09-29 11:26:43', 'Seems like a very good blog to me - first time I''ve seen one!  Love the ideas and the pictures - hope it all goes well universally and that you enjoy the rest of your year''s work.', 0, '1', 'Mozilla/5.0 (X11; U; Linux i686; en-GB; rv:1.9.2.8) Gecko/20100723 Ubuntu/9.10 (karmic) Firefox/3.6.8', '', 0, 0),
(4, 29, 'Anna', 'anna.marshall@pennineprospects.co.uk', '', '212.50.177.101', '2010-09-29 14:52:56', '2010-09-29 14:52:56', 'Your work is looking amazing Sally, I especially like the ''fake ruin'' piece - I see Frankie was helping out (or hindering?!) at Gaddings Dam.', 0, '1', 'Mozilla/4.0 (compatible; MSIE 7.0; Windows NT 5.2; .NET CLR 1.1.4322; .NET CLR 2.0.50727; .NET CLR 3.0.4506.2152; .NET CLR 3.5.30729)', '', 0, 0),
(5, 9, 'Angie Rogers', 'angie.rogers@talk21.com', 'http://www.angierogers.com', '81.135.81.167', '2010-09-30 08:42:40', '2010-09-30 08:42:40', 'Hi Sally\r\nWell done on getting this blog up and running.  I''m really looking forward to watching your work develop. Its interesting seeing another''s take on a lanscape I love and know so well.  \r\n\r\nThose Hushings at Hurstwood are so great aren''t they, the moor grass there always looks utterly strokeable.  I hope the recent horrible weather isn''t preventing you from getting on - I can recommend gore-tex over trousers as being a big help and can lend you mine for a while if you''re desperate.\r\nAll the best, Angie', 0, '1', 'Mozilla/5.0 (Macintosh; U; PPC Mac OS X; en-us) AppleWebKit/312.9 (KHTML, like Gecko) Safari/312.6', '', 0, 0),
(6, 81, 'sally', 'sally@sallybarker.org', 'http://sallybarker.org', '91.85.216.200', '2010-09-30 09:12:09', '2010-09-30 09:12:09', 'thanks steve- yes I believe the shale runs down the river beds with the water splitting it? I have to do my geology homework . I like this nerdy note to my voice!', 0, '1', 'Mozilla/5.0 (Windows; U; Windows NT 6.1; en-GB; rv:1.9.1.13) Gecko/20100914 Firefox/3.5.13', '', 2, 2),
(7, 9, 'jayne', 'jayne.mellor@btinternet.com', '', '86.152.251.50', '2010-10-01 19:56:21', '2010-10-01 19:56:21', 'Sal the project looks great - back to your roots kind of stuff. Love the shot of Top Withins, its a beautiful landscape and reminds me of the walk we go on to get to the Packhorse for a well deserved pint!! The cacti look really good you feel like you could prick your fingers on the ''spikes'' Well done for your work at Ravenscliffe - I''m sure you will have brought some happiness and smiles to those wo took part. Lots of love jayne xxx', 0, '1', 'Mozilla/4.0 (compatible; MSIE 7.0; Windows NT 6.0; BLNGBAR; GTB6.5; SLCC1; .NET CLR 2.0.50727; .NET CLR 3.5.21022; .NET CLR 3.5.30729; .NET CLR 3.0.30618; OfficeLiveConnector.1.3; OfficeLivePatch.0.0; .NET4.0C)', '', 0, 0),
(8, 9, 'Bryan', 'info@bryaneccleshall.co.uk', 'http://www.bryaneccleshall.co.uk', '81.105.139.165', '2010-10-11 09:14:10', '2010-10-11 09:14:10', 'Sally, this is looking like an interesting project. As ever, I like the way scale is moved back and forth. Large - monumental - things intimately remade and placed back into a full-size space. I know you''re interested in the making of things and what that means, but there''s a strong thread about what it is to be human - and particularly human-sized - in a world that often strives to be epic at the expense of the personal. Or maybe I''ve been reading Merleau-Ponty.', 0, '1', 'Mozilla/5.0 (Macintosh; U; Intel Mac OS X 10.5; en-US; rv:1.9.2.10) Gecko/20100914 Firefox/3.6.10', '', 0, 0),
(9, 9, 'sally', 'sally@sallybarker.org', 'http://sallybarker.org', '91.85.216.200', '2010-10-15 09:42:23', '2010-10-15 09:42:23', 'bryan\nyes, the distance between the intimate/ the personal space / the immediate space close by  and the epic/ vast is very much my focus and I''m glad you picked it up.\nThis is the nature of "good" landscape- it makes you feel and , yes,  in the well documented way of feeling small, vulnerable, insignificant, but there''s  more complexity as the realionship grows through excited, and scared, awed, powerless and powerful ...But it is this difference in scale that highlights &amp; starts to pull all of this into perspective (literally). The ridiculous nature of the tiny painted figures  as opposed to the absolute seriuosness of the real life incredible landscape. Excghange painted figures for a mocked up model of  Monument Valley made from sheep poo...\nI saw a Grand Canyon the other day- it was about a metere long, so I''m just going to take a fresh batch of figures up to occupy it.\nI will check out your Merleau-Ponty\ns', 0, '1', 'Mozilla/5.0 (Windows; U; Windows NT 6.1; en-GB; rv:1.9.2.10) Gecko/20100914 Firefox/3.6.10', '', 8, 2),
(10, 169, 'Anna', 'anna.marshall@pennineprospects.co.uk', '', '86.138.12.13', '2010-10-20 12:38:16', '2010-10-20 12:38:16', 'I like the populated stones - what a colourful bunch of explorers, I hope I meet a real human man in bight pink trousers on the Pennine moors....and I hope I have my camera if I do!  Great stuff Sally.  Enjoying reading the blog. Anna', 0, '1', 'Mozilla/4.0 (compatible; MSIE 8.0; Windows NT 5.1; Trident/4.0; GTB6.5; .NET CLR 2.0.50727; .NET CLR 1.1.4322)', '', 0, 0),
(11, 142, 'Sheila', 's_awhitaker@yahoo.co.uk', '', '86.145.231.146', '2010-10-20 15:45:22', '2010-10-20 15:45:22', 'I like the clash of landscapes/environments in the mud cactii image.', 0, '1', 'Mozilla/5.0 (Macintosh; U; PPC Mac OS X 10_4_11; en) AppleWebKit/533.18.1 (KHTML, like Gecko) Version/4.1.2 Safari/533.18.5', '', 0, 0),
(12, 142, 'Sheila', 's_awhitaker@yahoo.co.uk', '', '86.145.231.146', '2010-10-20 16:21:01', '2010-10-20 16:21:01', 'I didn''t read the cacti as anthroporphised.  I think they relate more to trees than people, but mainly they look weird.  \r\n\r\nIt''s interesting thinking about the Turner/Constable comparison.   You''re out there in the elements  on the moors.  I''m sitting here in my house in London and see the landscape around here (buffer lands - Wanstead flats, Hackney marshes -  you know these spaces too) as precious space  encroached upon massively by urban sprawl/industrialisation.  These spaces have escaped development only because they are protected - crown lands or whatever.  There are so many interventions in both landscapes - I was really interested in your Navvyopolis section and loved the compaison to the wild west films (themselves a fiction).   Something as simple as taking clay from the moors  to use is so elemental, but I notice your sense of nervousness about it - making sure you''ve got your permission letter on you, just in case.    Workshops using grass, bracken, mud, water sound so soothing and uplifting.  I think you are working with the landscape in a sympathetic respectful way using locally sourced materials. etc .    I think I''m just reflecting on the different characteristics of different interventions in the landscapes - sympathetic and the opposite of that, and very importantly how the perameters and constraints are set.   Looking forward to the next blog - love seeing the images - photos and drawings are great.', 0, '1', 'Mozilla/5.0 (Macintosh; U; PPC Mac OS X 10_4_11; en) AppleWebKit/533.18.1 (KHTML, like Gecko) Version/4.1.2 Safari/533.18.5', '', 0, 0),
(14, 142, 'sally', 'sally@sallybarker.org', 'http://sallybarker.org', '91.85.216.200', '2010-10-22 11:10:34', '2010-10-22 11:10:34', 'thanks, I''m loving this blog tool - being able to "publish" text with images (art and photos), it being appropriate to include my thoughts and recieving other peoples in return is a wonderful way to share work that is usually and primarily done in isolation. \nloved the things you are picking up - the interventions, the spreading mark &amp; influence of we humans on our environemnt- there are so many of us ! all wanting different things!\nHackney Marshes (sounds so deeply &amp; silently rural?), theres a great piece of landscape, so full of contradictions and edged with so many faces- the nature reserve, Kingsmead Estate, those BIG roads, the Olympic Park, Lee Valley, New Spitalfields market....its a fascinating place and I''ll bet hungry property developers have been wanting a piece of it for a long time.  Dis you ever see Simon Faithfulls film about navigating the River Lee?\nI am respectful of the materials and site but I want to distinguish myself from the Andy Goldsworthy worthiness because I percieve the landscape as being so much  more than Nature and stillness ... its a magnificent mirror, apart from everything else and reflects backwards and forwards, for ever and ever!!....\nWild West - places of exploration, where people go to claim parts of the land, re-invent/discover themselves, escape , The Wild West- somehow is the essence of human nature because we not only want to expand our knowledge and explore but we want to posess and populate as well, claim, make new rules. Always within the framework of the landscape and the land , which holds you in its vastness- that scale thing at work again, wooden shacks, tiny people, trying and succeeding in marking and building on the epic stage of the landscape', 0, '1', 'Mozilla/5.0 (Windows; U; Windows NT 6.1; en-GB; rv:1.9.2.11) Gecko/20101012 Firefox/3.6.11', '', 12, 2),
(17, 142, 'Sheila', 's_awhitaker@yahoo.co.uk', '', '86.145.233.30', '2010-10-25 22:00:41', '2010-10-25 22:00:41', 'Heaven forbid that I should have even hinted at any Andy Goldsworthy type worthiness!!!   It''s all soooooo much more interesting than that.  Will get back to you again another day -  need to go to bed and dream about tower block invasions and eerily lonesome pieces of tumble weed rolling around vast landscapes......  Saw some swans being very fierce and  territorial (I assume) up at Wanstead Park today - they were quite something.  sweet dreams!!', 0, '1', 'Mozilla/5.0 (Macintosh; U; PPC Mac OS X 10_4_11; en) AppleWebKit/533.18.1 (KHTML, like Gecko) Version/4.1.2 Safari/533.18.5', '', 14, 0),
(24, 178, 'Simon Warner', 'photos@simonwarner.co.uk', 'http://www.simonwarner.co.uk', '178.255.91.8', '2010-11-05 13:01:41', '2010-11-05 13:01:41', 'Was it Steve McQueen (the artist who rolled)? See also David Nash''s show at Yorkshire Sculpture Park – I think it was he who filmed a boulder over several years as it moved down a stream....\r\n\r\nGreat blog by the way', 0, '1', 'Mozilla/5.0 (Macintosh; U; Intel Mac OS X 10_6_3; en-us) AppleWebKit/531.21.11 (KHTML, like Gecko) Version/4.0.4 Safari/531.21.10', '', 0, 0),
(25, 178, 'sally', 'sally@sallybarker.org', 'http://sallybarker.org', '91.85.216.200', '2010-11-08 12:47:37', '2010-11-08 12:47:37', 'simon,\r\nsteve mcqueen made a film involving 3 cameras on a rolling barrel in manhattan (the beauty of wikipedia!), similar but the artist I''m thinking of did a much more raw, physical performance piece (though it took some time) and it definately happened through the filthy streets of South london, I remember thinking how much crap he would have picked up en route- I''ll do some more delving. Thanks for blogging.', 0, '1', 'Mozilla/5.0 (Windows; U; Windows NT 6.1; en-GB; rv:1.9.2.12) Gecko/20101026 Firefox/3.6.12', '', 0, 2),
(66, 279, 'Mags', 'm.j.stark@leeds.ac.uk', 'http://none', '129.11.76.229', '2010-12-06 15:15:24', '2010-12-06 15:15:24', 'Love the populus stuff you do. I''ve tried to do it myself and sometimes it works but I can never get rid of the stands the people are attached to.', 0, '1', 'Mozilla/5.0 (Windows; U; Windows NT 5.1; en-GB; rv:1.9.1.15) Gecko/20101026 Firefox/3.5.15 ( .NET CLR 3.5.30729; .NET4.0E)', '', 0, 0),
(349, 331, 'Sheila', 's_awhitaker@yahoo.co.uk', '', '86.145.239.169', '2011-01-16 22:58:08', '2011-01-16 22:58:08', 'The top photo looks so stark.  building an iglu might seem obvious, but such a fundamental need don''t you think?  heather and sheep poo would probably make quite an insulated shelter.  Think I''m thinking of fundamental needs and comfort .......  Must be careful you don''t catch cold up on those moors Sally!  \r\n\r\n Caitlin was making little shelters out of paper, cocktail sticks and blu tac this evening and I was talking to her about shelter from the sun.  Her models looked a bit like photo''s I''ve seen of bedouin tents in the desert.   I was imagining the dark shadow cast by a canopy type shelter on a sun baked deset sand scape.  Stark contrasts of shadow and sand, and also  sharp contrast to the environment in your pictures  - different kind of shelter required.  Have just realised it is me who is going on about shelters (not surprising as we are in the throws of trying to move house and feeling a bit vulnerable, maybe), you just wondered weather to build an igloo.   Also I noticed you comenting that the sheep had been sheltering by the Bride stone, which looks like an amazing shape.  looks like it should be unstable, but isn''t.\r\n\r\n10 mins later - have just looked further into your recent posts and seen the heather and  little house photos.  It looks very sturdy and solid set against the snow - I really like it.  Also the description/photo of the heather stems - the raw material, which looks fantastic in itself.', 0, '1', 'Mozilla/4.0 (compatible; MSIE 8.0; Windows NT 6.0; Trident/4.0; GTB5; SLCC1; .NET CLR 2.0.50727; Media Center PC 5.0; .NET CLR 3.5.30729; .NET CLR 3.0.30729; .NET4.0C; MSN OptimizedIE8;ENGB)', '', 0, 0),
(325, 309, 'Mark Reed', 'm.reed@abdn.ac.uk', 'http://www.see.leeds.ac.uk/sustainableuplands', '81.156.232.114', '2010-12-23 10:36:38', '2010-12-23 10:36:38', 'I love this. A living landscape in which people make a living, and yet are dwarfed by the upland landscape and all it provides to the rest of society...', 0, '1', 'Mozilla/5.0 (Windows; U; Windows NT 5.1; en-US) AppleWebKit/534.10 (KHTML, like Gecko) Chrome/8.0.552.224 Safari/534.10', '', 0, 0),
(94, 279, 'sally', 'sally@sallybarker.org', 'http://sallybarker.org', '91.85.216.200', '2010-12-08 22:51:05', '2010-12-08 22:51:05', 'ahh, a real comment, not spam!\nthe figures are 1: 200 or 1:100 and bought in groups- maybe 16 on each "stem"- like brussel sprouts! So when you twist them off the stem they come away pretty clean.\nThey are attached by the head (!) so a little fine sandpapering for any blobby heads/ weird hairdo''s.\nGood to have proper comment to reply to- its been spam for the past month.\nI have a lovely snowy post coming up- soooo cold up there.\nWhat work do you do?', 0, '1', 'Mozilla/5.0 (Windows; U; Windows NT 6.1; en-GB; rv:1.9.2.12) Gecko/20101026 Firefox/3.6.12', '', 66, 2),
(384, 9, 'Caren', 'carensmith@msn.com', '', '81.158.99.124', '2011-05-19 10:01:28', '2011-05-19 10:01:28', 'Hi Sally ... inspirational!  It would be wonderful to position this as part of our ''Artists by the Way'' exbn at WCC 25th June-10th July.  Would be fab!  Well done ... look forward to learning more and talking further!  Cx', 0, '1', 'Mozilla/5.0 (Macintosh; U; Intel Mac OS X 10_5_8; en-us) AppleWebKit/533.20.25 (KHTML, like Gecko) Version/5.0.4 Safari/533.20.27', '', 0, 0),
(371, 9, 'Nancy Stedman', 'nancy.stedman@naturalengland.org.uk', '', '62.25.109.195', '2011-04-04 13:26:04', '2011-04-04 13:26:04', 'Hi Sally\r\nI have only just found this blog - it''s great, and I love the ideas and the images!  I''ve circulated a couple of them to some colleagues here at Natural England, who know the area well - how I wish I had found them in time for Friday 1 April...! - they are going down very well, provoking surprise and laughter and admiration.   The camels look so at home in that environment.  As for the scaffolding - someone''s blood pressure went rocketing - what''t this, doesn''t it need planning permission??!! - before they realised...  \r\nI''m so pleased that you are off to such a good start.  I''ll look forward to seeing your exhibition, all the best, Nancy', 0, '1', 'Mozilla/4.0 (compatible; MSIE 7.0; Windows NT 6.0; SLCC1; .NET CLR 2.0.50727; .NET CLR 3.0.04506; InfoPath.2)', '', 0, 0),
(378, 357, 'Sheila', 's_awhitaker@yahoo.co.uk', '', '86.160.206.234', '2011-04-18 10:36:05', '2011-04-18 10:36:05', 'Love these.   It all looks very precarious.', 0, '1', 'Mozilla/5.0 (Macintosh; U; PPC Mac OS X 10_4_11; en) AppleWebKit/533.19.4 (KHTML, like Gecko) Version/4.1.3 Safari/533.19.4', '', 0, 0),
(356, 261, 'char march', 'charlottemarch@btinternet.com', 'http://www.charmarch.co.uk', '86.172.74.34', '2011-01-22 18:15:31', '2011-01-22 18:15:31', 'how did the recordings turn out?  and wot equipment did u use?  wld love to hear them. C x', 0, '1', 'Mozilla/4.0 (compatible; MSIE 7.0; Windows NT 6.0; YPC 3.2.0; SLCC1; .NET CLR 2.0.50727; Media Center PC 5.0; .NET CLR 3.5.30729; .NET CLR 3.0.30729; .NET4.0C; OfficeLiveConnector.1.5; OfficeLivePatch.1.3)', '', 0, 0),
(357, 249, 'char march', 'charlottemarch@btinternet.com', 'http://www.charmarch.co.uk', '86.172.74.34', '2011-01-22 18:16:53', '2011-01-22 18:16:53', 'love these - wot a lot of v v different styles and ideas coming through.  great stuff!', 0, '1', 'Mozilla/4.0 (compatible; MSIE 7.0; Windows NT 6.0; YPC 3.2.0; SLCC1; .NET CLR 2.0.50727; Media Center PC 5.0; .NET CLR 3.5.30729; .NET CLR 3.0.30729; .NET4.0C; OfficeLiveConnector.1.5; OfficeLivePatch.1.3)', '', 0, 0),
