(62, 2, '2010-09-21 12:23:30', '2010-09-21 12:23:30', 'This is my first blog entry for The Watershed Project- I''ve never blogged before so I''ll cross my fingers and take a deep breath.\r\n\r\nFollowing the call out for artists in march-  http://www.pennineprospects.co.uk/watershed-landscape/inspiration - I was selected as the artist for the first of 3 years. There is also a writer for each year-  so my writing mate is Andrew Mc Millan- I''m hoping we get to do something collaborative.\r\n\r\n<a rel="attachment wp-att-43" href="http://watershed.sallybarker.local/catch-up/monument-valley-at-gorple-s-2/"><img class="alignnone size-medium wp-image-43" title="Monument Valley at Gorple Reservoir" src="http://watershed.sallybarker.local/files/2010/09/Monument-Valley-at-Gorple-s-640x426.jpg" alt="" width="640" height="426" /></a>\r\n\r\nthis is an image I put together to visualise my proposal- Monument Valley at Gorple- its a rough sketch. Monument valley is made from sheep poo &amp; is about 10 cm tall- photoshopped in front of a view across the moors towards Gorple Reservoir.\r\n\r\nI started the project in August. My plan is to twin locations on the moors with locations around the world- sites will be chosen for their similarities or contrasts , a tension that pulls them together. The foreign elelements will be made using natural materials found on the moors- sheep poo, bracken, mud etc.  I have done a couple of quick sketches so far, so I''m not just talking about the work- Camels at The Hushings - anyone who has visited The Hushings will see its a dry , harsh landscape, looking a lot like sand dunes-  formed when  the land was "rinsed" to relinquish its precious limestone.\r\n\r\n<a rel="attachment wp-att-45" href="http://watershed.sallybarker.local/catch-up/camels-over-hushings-s-3/"><img class="alignnone size-medium wp-image-45" title="Camels over the hushings" src="http://watershed.sallybarker.local/files/2010/09/camels-over-hushings-s-640x426.jpg" alt="" width="640" height="426" /></a>\r\n\r\nPhotography, photoshop and good old fashioned modelling combine to create the images.\r\n\r\nI am initially researching locations in the upper landscape of the moors - this most amazing of places. The area i am concentrating on is the gorgeous wild bit between Hebden Bridge- Haworth and Burnley- but I''ll go anywhere.\r\n\r\nI have explored, photographed (and picked up sheep poo) - around Widdop , Withens Clough , The Bridestones, Top Withins, Walshaw Dean, Gaddings Dam.\r\n\r\nhere are some of the sites I am interested in using\r\n\r\nThis is part of The Bridestones\r\n\r\n<a rel="attachment wp-att-44" href="http://watershed.sallybarker.local/catch-up/bridestones-aug-10-2/"><img class="alignnone size-medium wp-image-44" title="The Bridestones aug 2010" src="http://watershed.sallybarker.local/files/2010/09/bridestones-aug-10-640x426.jpg" alt="" width="640" height="426" /></a>', 'intro to The Watershed -inspired by landscape project. Sally Barker', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '9-revision-12', '', '', '2010-09-21 12:23:30', '2010-09-21 12:23:30', '', 9, 'http://watershed.sallybarker.local/9-revision-12/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
